Shimizu Yanagikita No. 1 Kofun was discovered within the Second Numazu Industrial Complex and later relocated within the same area.{{Sfn|Heibonsha Place name Data Center|2000}} An investigation in [[1986]] (Shōwa 61) confirmed its structure as a {{ill|Jōen-kahō-fun|ja|上円下方墳|1=Joenkahofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with a lower rectangular section overlain by an upper circular section. Surrounding the tomb is a rectangular moat about 1 meter wide and 20 meters along each side. burial goods primarily consist of {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, dating the tomb to the early {{ill|8th century|ja|8世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Yamamoto|2009|p=9}}

== Excavation History ==
The presence of Kofuns in the area had been known for some time. During a detailed survey in [[1985]] (Shōwa 60), associated with the development of the Second Numazu Industrial Complex, a circular Kofun was identified at the center of the ridge and named "Shimizu Yanagikita No. 1 Kofun." Two additional mounds were identified to the south and named No. 2 and No. 3 Kofun. A pre-construction excavation in [[1986]] (Shōwa 61) revealed that Shimizu Yanagikita No. 1 Kofun was a {{ill|Jōen-kahō-fun|ja|上円下方墳|1=Joenkahofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. A stone casket was discovered in the moat.{{Sfn|Numazu City History Compilation Committee & Education Board|2002|p=391}}{{Sfn|Numazu City Education Board|1990|p=404}}

== area ==
* Elevation: 145–165 meters
* Northern side: 20.3 meters
* Western side: 20.2 meters
* Eastern side: 20.0 meters
* Southern side: 20.2 meters{{Sfn|Numazu City History Compilation Committee & Education Board|2002|p=393}}

== burial goods ==
=== Stone Casket ===
* A stone casket was found buried in a hollow on the eastern side of the moat. The casket was primarily composed of three pieces of {{ill|tuff|ja|凝灰岩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Fragments scattered by later agricultural activities were also discovered. The casket features a central circular depression about 35 cm in diameter, but no burial-related items such as urns or cremated remains were found nearby.{{Sfn|Numazu City Education Board|1990|p=414}}
* The tuff matches the material used in hollowed stone coffins from tomb groups near the base of Mount Ashitaka. Locally, the tuff is referred to as "Numazu tuff," originating from the Shizuura area.{{Sfn|Numazu City Education Board|1990|p=424}}

=== Sue Ware ===
* Sue pottery fragments, including lids, bowls, and long-necked jars, were recovered from the soil near the mound, suggesting their association with the tomb. These items are thought to date to the early {{ill|8th century|ja|8世紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, although some later burial goods indicate continued ritual use.{{Sfn|Numazu City Education Board|1990|pp=418,687}}
* Most Sue pottery fragments are bluish-gray, likely originating from {{ill|Kosei Kiln|ja|湖西窯|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. However, some greenish-gray pieces, such as bowl lids, are attributed to {{ill|Sanage Kiln|ja|猿投窯|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.{{Sfn|Yamamoto|2009|p=12}}

== Current Intypeation ==
'''location'''
* Numazu Industrial Complex, Ashitaka-Ogami, Numazu City, Shizuoka Prefecture
[[File:Shimizuyanagi Kita1 Sekihitsu.jpg|thumb|Replica of the stone casket from Shimizu Yanagikita No. 1 Kofun]]

'''Related Facility'''
* {{ill|Numazu City Historic Site Center|ja|沼津市文化財センター|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Numazu City, Shige) houses burial goods from Shimizu Yanagikita No. 1 Kofun.

